1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:17,000
So how do we learn?

2
00:00:17,000 --> 00:00:21,639
And why do some of us learn things more easily than others?

3
00:00:21,639 --> 00:00:26,559
So as I was mentioning, I'm Dr. Laura Boyd, I'm a brain researcher here at the University

4
00:00:26,559 --> 00:00:27,559
of British Columbia.

5
00:00:28,559 --> 00:00:35,840
These are the questions that fascinate me.

6
00:00:35,840 --> 00:00:41,560
So brain research is one of the great frontiers in the understanding of human physiology and

7
00:00:41,560 --> 00:00:45,959
also in the consideration of what makes us who we are.

8
00:00:45,959 --> 00:00:50,080
It's an amazing time to be a brain researcher and I would argue to you that I have the most

9
00:00:50,080 --> 00:00:52,720
interesting job in the world.

10
00:00:52,720 --> 00:00:57,480
What we know about the brain is changing at a breathtaking pace and much of what we

11
00:00:57,480 --> 00:01:03,599
thought we knew and understood about the brain turns out to be not true or incomplete.

12
00:01:03,599 --> 00:01:07,320
Now some of these misconceptions are more obvious than others.

13
00:01:07,320 --> 00:01:14,080
For example, we used to think that after childhood the brain did not, really could not change

14
00:01:14,080 --> 00:01:18,559
and it turns out that nothing could be farther from the truth.

15
00:01:18,559 --> 00:01:22,400
Another misconception about the brain is that you only use parts of it at any given

16
00:01:22,400 --> 00:01:25,800
time and silent when you do nothing.

17
00:01:25,800 --> 00:01:27,480
This is also untrue.

18
00:01:27,480 --> 00:01:32,480
It turns out that even when you're at rest and thinking of nothing, your brain is highly

19
00:01:32,480 --> 00:01:33,480
active.

20
00:01:33,480 --> 00:01:38,760
So it's been advances in technology such as MRI has allowed us to make these and many

21
00:01:38,760 --> 00:01:41,199
other important discoveries.

22
00:01:41,199 --> 00:01:45,839
And perhaps the most exciting, the most interesting and transformative of these discoveries is

23
00:01:45,839 --> 00:01:51,760
that every time you learn a new fact or skill, you change your brain.

24
00:01:51,760 --> 00:01:54,879
It's something we call neuroplasticity.

25
00:01:54,879 --> 00:01:59,720
So as little as 25 years ago, we thought that after about puberty, the only changes that

26
00:01:59,720 --> 00:02:01,800
took place in the brain were negative.

27
00:02:01,800 --> 00:02:06,980
The loss of brain cells with aging, the result of damage like a stroke.

28
00:02:06,980 --> 00:02:13,880
And then studies began to show remarkable amounts of reorganization in the adult brain.

29
00:02:13,919 --> 00:02:20,160
And the assuming research has shown us that all of our behaviors change our brain.

30
00:02:20,160 --> 00:02:24,740
That these changes are not limited by age, it's good news, right?

31
00:02:24,740 --> 00:02:27,839
And in fact, they're taking place all the time.

32
00:02:27,839 --> 00:02:33,160
And very importantly, brain reorganization helps to support recovery after you damage

33
00:02:33,160 --> 00:02:35,039
your brain.

34
00:02:35,039 --> 00:02:39,660
The key to each of these changes is neuroplasticity.

35
00:02:39,660 --> 00:02:41,559
So what does it look like?

36
00:02:41,559 --> 00:02:46,160
Your brain can change in three very basic ways to support learning.

37
00:02:46,160 --> 00:02:47,479
And the first is chemical.

38
00:02:47,479 --> 00:02:52,759
So your brain actually functions by transferring chemical signals between brain cells, what

39
00:02:52,759 --> 00:02:57,759
we call neurons, and these trigger a series of actions and reactions.

40
00:02:57,759 --> 00:03:02,320
So to support learning, your brain can increase the amount or the concentrations of these

41
00:03:02,320 --> 00:03:06,559
chemical signaling that's taking place between neurons.

42
00:03:06,559 --> 00:03:11,000
Now because this kind of change can happen very rapidly, this supports short-term memory

43
00:03:11,000 --> 00:03:15,720
or the short-term improvement in the performance of a motor skill.

44
00:03:15,720 --> 00:03:21,619
The second way that the brain can change to support learning is by altering its structure.

45
00:03:21,619 --> 00:03:25,639
So during learning, the brain can change the connections between neurons.

46
00:03:25,639 --> 00:03:29,399
Now here, the physical structure of the brain is actually changing, so this takes a bit

47
00:03:29,399 --> 00:03:31,080
more time.

48
00:03:31,080 --> 00:03:35,720
These types of changes are related to long-term memory, the long-term improvement in a motor

49
00:03:35,720 --> 00:03:36,960
skill.

50
00:03:36,960 --> 00:03:41,679
Now these processes, they interact, and let me give you an example of how.

51
00:03:41,679 --> 00:03:47,320
So we've all tried to learn a new motor skill, maybe playing the piano, maybe learning to

52
00:03:47,320 --> 00:03:48,320
juggle.

53
00:03:48,320 --> 00:03:53,199
And you've had the experience of getting better and better within a single session of practice

54
00:03:53,199 --> 00:03:55,960
and thinking, I've got it.

55
00:03:55,960 --> 00:03:59,759
And then maybe you've returned the next day and all those improvements from the day before,

56
00:03:59,759 --> 00:04:01,679
they're lost.

57
00:04:01,679 --> 00:04:02,679
What happened?

58
00:04:03,000 --> 00:04:07,320
Well, in the short-term, your brain was able to increase the chemical signaling between

59
00:04:07,320 --> 00:04:08,320
your neurons.

60
00:04:08,320 --> 00:04:14,720
But for some reason, those changes did not induce the structural change that are necessary

61
00:04:14,720 --> 00:04:17,760
to support long-term memory.

62
00:04:17,760 --> 00:04:22,480
Remember that long-term memories take time, and what you see in the short-term does not

63
00:04:22,480 --> 00:04:24,160
reflect learning.

64
00:04:24,160 --> 00:04:28,260
It's these physical changes that are now going to support long-term memories and chemical

65
00:04:28,260 --> 00:04:33,260
changes that support short-term memories.

66
00:04:33,260 --> 00:04:37,739
Structural changes also can lead to integrated networks of brain regions that function together

67
00:04:37,739 --> 00:04:39,459
to support learning.

68
00:04:39,459 --> 00:04:44,179
And they can also lead to certain brain regions that are important for very specific behaviors

69
00:04:44,179 --> 00:04:46,980
to change their structure or to enlarge.

70
00:04:46,980 --> 00:04:49,339
So here's some examples of that.

71
00:04:49,339 --> 00:04:54,760
So people who read Braille, they have larger hand sensory areas in their brain than those

72
00:04:54,760 --> 00:04:57,019
of us who don't.

73
00:04:57,019 --> 00:05:02,220
Your dominant hand motor region, which is on the left side of your brain if you're right-handed,

74
00:05:02,220 --> 00:05:04,899
is larger than the other side.

75
00:05:04,899 --> 00:05:10,299
And research shows that London taxicab drivers who actually have to memorize a map of London

76
00:05:10,299 --> 00:05:16,220
to get their taxicab license, they have larger brain regions devoted to spatial or mapping

77
00:05:16,220 --> 00:05:18,019
memories.

78
00:05:18,019 --> 00:05:24,100
Now the last way that your brain can change to support learning is by altering its function.

79
00:05:24,100 --> 00:05:29,619
As you use a brain region, it becomes more and more excitable and easy to use again.

80
00:05:29,619 --> 00:05:34,179
And as your brain has these areas that increase their excitability, the brain shifts how and

81
00:05:34,179 --> 00:05:36,420
when they're activated.

82
00:05:36,420 --> 00:05:42,579
With learning, we see that whole networks of brain activity are shifting and changing.

83
00:05:42,579 --> 00:05:48,980
So neuroplasticity is supported by chemical, by structural, and by functional changes.

84
00:05:48,980 --> 00:05:51,640
And these are happening across the whole brain.

85
00:05:51,640 --> 00:05:57,760
They can occur in isolation from one another, but most often they take place in concert.

86
00:05:57,760 --> 00:05:59,720
Together they support learning.

87
00:05:59,720 --> 00:06:04,279
And they're taking place all the time.

88
00:06:04,279 --> 00:06:09,079
So I've just told you really how awesomely neuroplastic your brain is.

89
00:06:09,079 --> 00:06:13,279
So why can't you learn anything you choose to with ease?

90
00:06:13,279 --> 00:06:17,160
Why do our kids sometimes fail in school?

91
00:06:17,160 --> 00:06:20,880
Why as we age do we tend to forget things?

92
00:06:20,920 --> 00:06:24,640
And why don't people fully recover from brain damage?

93
00:06:24,640 --> 00:06:29,799
That is, what is it that limits and facilitates neuroplasticity?

94
00:06:29,799 --> 00:06:31,279
And so this is what I study.

95
00:06:31,279 --> 00:06:35,880
I study it specifically how it relates to recovery from stroke.

96
00:06:35,880 --> 00:06:39,799
So recently stroke dropped from being the third leading cause of death in the United

97
00:06:39,799 --> 00:06:42,959
States to be the fourth leading cause of death.

98
00:06:42,959 --> 00:06:45,079
Great news, right?

99
00:06:45,079 --> 00:06:49,399
What actually turns out that the numbers of people having a stroke has not declined.

100
00:06:49,399 --> 00:06:53,480
We're just better at keeping people alive after a severe stroke.

101
00:06:53,480 --> 00:06:58,519
It turns out to be very difficult to help the brain recover from stroke.

102
00:06:58,519 --> 00:07:05,799
And frankly we have failed to develop effective rehabilitation interventions.

103
00:07:05,799 --> 00:07:12,079
The net result of this is that stroke is the leading cause of long-term disability in adults

104
00:07:12,079 --> 00:07:14,279
in the world.

105
00:07:14,279 --> 00:07:19,279
Individuals with stroke are younger and tending to live longer with that disability.

106
00:07:19,279 --> 00:07:22,959
And research from my group actually shows that the health-related quality of life of

107
00:07:22,959 --> 00:07:26,559
Canadians with stroke has declined.

108
00:07:26,559 --> 00:07:30,519
So clearly we need to be better at helping people recover from stroke.

109
00:07:30,519 --> 00:07:36,980
And this is an enormous societal problem and it's one that we're not solving.

110
00:07:36,980 --> 00:07:39,119
So what can be done?

111
00:07:39,119 --> 00:07:41,359
One thing is absolutely clear.

112
00:07:41,359 --> 00:07:46,839
The best driver of neuroplastic change in your brain is your behavior.

113
00:07:46,839 --> 00:07:51,440
The problem is that the dose of behavior, the dose of practice that's required to learn

114
00:07:51,440 --> 00:07:55,880
new and relearn old motor skills, it's very large.

115
00:07:55,880 --> 00:08:00,799
And how to effectively deliver these large doses of practice is a very difficult problem.

116
00:08:00,799 --> 00:08:03,359
It's also a very expensive problem.

117
00:08:03,359 --> 00:08:07,239
So the approach that my research has taken is to develop therapies that prime or that

118
00:08:07,239 --> 00:08:09,600
prepare the brain to learn.

119
00:08:09,600 --> 00:08:14,760
And these have included brain stimulation, exercise, and robotics.

120
00:08:14,760 --> 00:08:20,079
But through my research, I've realized that a major limitation to the development of therapies

121
00:08:20,079 --> 00:08:25,959
that speed recovery from stroke is that patterns of neuroplasticity are highly variable from

122
00:08:25,959 --> 00:08:28,679
person to person.

123
00:08:28,679 --> 00:08:32,919
Now as a researcher, variability used to drive me crazy.

124
00:08:32,919 --> 00:08:38,559
It makes it very difficult to use statistics to test your data and your ideas.

125
00:08:38,960 --> 00:08:45,479
Because of this, medical intervention studies are specifically designed to minimize variability.

126
00:08:45,479 --> 00:08:50,760
But in my research, it's becoming really clear that the most important, the most informative

127
00:08:50,760 --> 00:08:56,719
data that we collect is showing this variability.

128
00:08:56,719 --> 00:09:01,280
So by studying the brain after stroke, we've learned a lot.

129
00:09:01,280 --> 00:09:06,760
And I think these lessons are very valuable in other areas.

130
00:09:06,760 --> 00:09:12,239
So the first lesson is that the primary driver of change in your brain is your behavior.

131
00:09:12,239 --> 00:09:16,320
So there's no neuroplasticity drug you can take.

132
00:09:16,320 --> 00:09:19,559
Nothing is more effective than practice at helping you learn.

133
00:09:19,559 --> 00:09:24,280
And the bottom line is, you have to do the work.

134
00:09:24,280 --> 00:09:29,479
And in fact, my research has shown that increased difficulty, increased struggle, if you will,

135
00:09:29,479 --> 00:09:35,039
during practice, actually leads to both more learning and greater structural change in

136
00:09:35,039 --> 00:09:38,000
the brain.

137
00:09:38,000 --> 00:09:42,799
The problem here is, is that neuroplasticity can work both ways.

138
00:09:42,799 --> 00:09:44,320
It can be positive.

139
00:09:44,320 --> 00:09:47,960
You learn something new, and you've refined a motor skill.

140
00:09:47,960 --> 00:09:49,799
It also can be negative, though.

141
00:09:49,799 --> 00:09:51,840
You forgot something you once knew.

142
00:09:51,840 --> 00:09:54,200
You become addicted to drugs.

143
00:09:54,200 --> 00:09:55,520
Maybe you have chronic pain.

144
00:09:55,520 --> 00:10:01,479
So your brain is tremendously plastic, and it's being shaped both structurally and functionally

145
00:10:01,479 --> 00:10:07,159
by everything you do, but also by everything that you don't do.

146
00:10:07,159 --> 00:10:12,080
The second lesson we've learned about the brain is that there is no one-size-fits-all

147
00:10:12,080 --> 00:10:14,520
approach to learning.

148
00:10:14,520 --> 00:10:17,280
So there's no recipe for learning.

149
00:10:17,280 --> 00:10:21,840
Consider the popular belief that it takes 10,000 hours of practice to learn and to master

150
00:10:21,840 --> 00:10:23,760
a new motor skill.

151
00:10:23,760 --> 00:10:27,200
Now I can assure you, it is not quite that simple.

152
00:10:27,200 --> 00:10:31,200
For some of us, it's going to take a lot more practice, and for others, it may take

153
00:10:31,200 --> 00:10:33,080
far less.

154
00:10:33,080 --> 00:10:37,880
So the shaping of our plastic brains, it's far too unique for there to be any single

155
00:10:37,880 --> 00:10:41,359
intervention that's going to work for all of us.

156
00:10:41,359 --> 00:10:46,619
And now this realization has forced us to consider something called personalized medicine.

157
00:10:46,619 --> 00:10:53,179
So this is the idea that to optimize outcomes, each individual requires their own intervention.

158
00:10:53,179 --> 00:10:55,960
And the idea actually comes from cancer treatments.

159
00:10:55,960 --> 00:11:01,479
And here it turns out that genetics are very important in matching certain types of chemotherapy

160
00:11:01,479 --> 00:11:04,679
with specific forms of cancer.

161
00:11:04,679 --> 00:11:08,500
My research is showing that this also applies to recovery from stroke.

162
00:11:08,500 --> 00:11:12,739
So there are certain characteristics of brain structure and function that we call biomarkers.

163
00:11:12,739 --> 00:11:18,880
And these biomarkers are proving to be very helpful in helping us to match specific therapies

164
00:11:18,880 --> 00:11:21,320
with individual patients.

165
00:11:21,320 --> 00:11:25,659
And the data from my lab suggests it's a combination of biomarkers that best predicts

166
00:11:25,659 --> 00:11:29,640
neuroplastic change and patterns of recovery after stroke.

167
00:11:29,640 --> 00:11:34,460
And that's not surprising, given how complicated the human brain is.

168
00:11:34,460 --> 00:11:40,179
But I also think we can consider this concept much more broadly.

169
00:11:40,179 --> 00:11:44,799
Given the unique structure and function of each of our brains, what we've learned about

170
00:11:44,799 --> 00:11:51,159
neuroplasticity after stroke applies to everyone.

171
00:11:52,000 --> 00:11:55,080
The behaviors that you employ in your everyday life are important.

172
00:11:55,080 --> 00:11:57,760
Each of them is changing your brain.

173
00:11:57,760 --> 00:12:03,440
And I believe we have to consider not just personalized medicine, but personalized learning.

174
00:12:03,440 --> 00:12:09,479
The uniqueness of your brain will affect you, both as a learner and also as a teacher.

175
00:12:09,479 --> 00:12:15,239
And now this idea helps us to understand why some children can thrive in traditional education

176
00:12:15,239 --> 00:12:17,640
settings and others don't.

177
00:12:17,640 --> 00:12:25,719
Why some of us can learn languages easily and yet others can pick up any sport and excel.

178
00:12:25,719 --> 00:12:31,400
So when you leave this room today, your brain will not be the same as when you entered this

179
00:12:31,400 --> 00:12:33,200
morning.

180
00:12:33,200 --> 00:12:36,559
And I think that's pretty amazing.

181
00:12:36,559 --> 00:12:41,479
But each of you is going to have changed your brain differently.

182
00:12:41,479 --> 00:12:46,880
Understanding these differences, these individual patterns, this variability and change, is

183
00:12:46,880 --> 00:12:50,159
going to enable the next great advance in neuroscience.

184
00:12:50,159 --> 00:12:54,440
It's going to allow us to develop new and more effective interventions and allow for

185
00:12:54,440 --> 00:13:01,039
matches between learners and teachers and patients and interventions.

186
00:13:01,039 --> 00:13:04,080
And this does not just apply to recovery from stroke.

187
00:13:04,080 --> 00:13:09,880
It applies to each of us as a parent, as a teacher, as a manager, and also because you're

188
00:13:09,880 --> 00:13:13,919
at TEDx today, a lifelong learner.

189
00:13:13,960 --> 00:13:17,359
Study how and what you learn best.

190
00:13:17,359 --> 00:13:20,919
Repeat those behaviors that are healthy for your brain.

191
00:13:20,919 --> 00:13:24,679
And break those behaviors and habits that are not.

192
00:13:24,679 --> 00:13:26,520
Practice.

193
00:13:26,520 --> 00:13:30,760
Learning is about doing the work that your brain requires.

194
00:13:30,760 --> 00:13:34,760
So the best strategies are going to vary between individuals.

195
00:13:34,760 --> 00:13:35,760
You know what?

196
00:13:35,760 --> 00:13:37,679
They're even going to vary within individuals.

197
00:13:37,679 --> 00:13:42,640
So for you, learning music may come very easily, but learning to snowboard?

198
00:13:42,640 --> 00:13:43,640
Much harder.

199
00:13:43,640 --> 00:13:50,159
I hope that you leave today with a new appreciation of how magnificent your brain is.

200
00:13:50,159 --> 00:13:55,359
You and your plastic brain are constantly being shaped by the world around you.

201
00:13:55,359 --> 00:14:00,080
Understand that everything you do, everything you encounter, and everything you experience

202
00:14:00,080 --> 00:14:01,679
is changing your brain.

203
00:14:01,679 --> 00:14:06,000
And that can be for better, but it can also be for worse.

204
00:14:06,000 --> 00:14:10,840
So when you leave today, go out and build the brain you want.

205
00:14:10,840 --> 00:14:11,599
Thank you very much.

